{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_kaffirlily_ver01/data/sn82007637/00340580382/1945081001/0974.xml":{"full_text":"Cj\nOrganize Toledo\n100%\nCf\nTokdo Is Scene Of Basic\nStrikebreaking Course\nToledo became the scene of the Army\u2019s basic training\ncourse for handling postwar strikes last Friday, when 350\nhelmeted military policemen with bayonets in place arrived\nat Scott Park to \u201csolve a problem\u201d of removing \u201csnipers\u201d\n^rom the old Toledo University building located in the park.\nThe peculiar thing was that\nthe \u201csnipers\u201d, also M. P.\u2019s,\nwho had arrived earlier in the\nday, were dressed in* civilian\nclothe. when they took over the\nold University building. They\ncarried buckets of sand and dirt\nand a hose into the building\nwith them.\nWhen the troops arrived in\nthe afternoon, Capt. Paul Gillis\ncommanding, went to the build\ning and read the \u201csnipers\u201d the\nriot act and demanded that they\nevacuate. The peculair thing\nwas that the troops under Capt.\nGillis did not refer to the\n\u201csnipers\u201d as snipers, but as\nstrikers, and as the proceedings\nwore on, it became obvious that\nthe soldiers were not being\ntrained for war duties, but for\nStrike breaking.\nsnip\nwith\nterri\nquiet\nActions of the so-called\ners was not in keeping\nthose of snipers in enemy\ntory. Instead of keeping\nand firing as snipers do, the\n\u201cstrikers\u201d jeered the Captain\nafter he had read them the riot\nact. Cries of \u201ccome and get us,\u2019\u2019\n\u201cWhat are you waiting for,\u201d and\ninsults were hurled at the\ntroopers.\nCaptain Gillis explained that\nit had\ntroops\nmeans\nto the\nand factories in the vicinity this\nplan had been abandoned. In\nstead, smoke pots were placed\nnear', the building and-.as the\nasmoke rolled toward the strik\ners, the troops made their at\ntack.\nbeen the intention of the\nto remove the men by\nof tear gas, but that due\nclose proximity of homes\nAttackers succeeded in reach\ning the second floor of the build\ning but could not reach the\nstrikers who had retreated to the\nroof. The besieged men had\npulled a ladder up after them\nwhich they had used to reach\nthe building\u2019s top. Then, iron\nically, the wind changed and\nblew the smoke toward the at\ntackers and the umpire Maj. J.\nContinued on Page 2\nToledo~UAW-CIO\nTo\nMark\nAnniversary\nMembers of the United Auto\nInobile Workers-CIO will cele\nbrate the 10th anniversary of\nthe founding of their Union on\nAugust 25 with appropriate\nceremonies to mark the event\naccording to Walter Madrzy\nkewski, international UAW-CIO\nrepresentative of Regional Di\nrector\u2019s Richard Gosser\u2019s staff,\nChairman of the committee in\nCharge of arrangements.\nTentative plans are now being\nconsidered for honoring the day\n\u00a9n which the UAW-CIO was or\nganized. Details will\nnounced as soon as the\nhas been arranged.\n\u201cTen years ago, we\nidea that the UAW-CIO would\nturn out to be such a large and\npowerful organization,\nwe are \u2018u~\ngressive\nCountry\namount\naiid out\nIt is fitting and proper that we\npause on the anniversary of the\nfirst decade of our existance to\nlook back at the past and view\nthe future,\u201d said Mr. Madrzy\nkowski.\nbe an\nprogram\nhad no\nToday,\none of the really pro\norganizations in this\nwhich is doing a large\nof good work both in\nof the labor movement.\nA banquet will climax the ob\nservation of the foundation of\nthe organization with local civic,\nreligious and labor leaders as\nguests. Mr. Madrzykowski ex\nplained that while the plans\nwere nearly completed and\nwould be withheld until the\nprogram was completed.\nTurin In WTOL Thursday At 1 p. m.\nKlopping Vets Get Bonus\nMembers of the A. C. Klop\nping Unit of Local 12, UAW\nCIO will benefit as a result of a\nsupplementary agreement to\nthe Unit contract signed earlier\nthis year. Terms of the supple\nment are that any employee of\nthe company who has, or who\nmay enter the armed forces of\nthe United States while at war,\nshall receive their accumulated\nvacation bonus, provided they\nare re-employed within 90 days\nafter discharge, and have work\ned 30 day# after being re-em\nployed.\nFull Employment Bill\nMass Meeting\nTo Be Heid\nSunday\nthe\nA mass protest against\nlittle steel formula and accu\nmulated resentment of the work\ners against the War Labor Board\nwill find outlet next Sunday\nwhen Toledo members of the\nUAW-CIO meet at Civic Audi\ntorium next Sunday afternoon\nin a mass demonstration.\nThe meeting, one of hundreds\nto be held throughout the coun\ntry wherever there are UAW\nCIO Local Unions, is the out\ngrowth of action taken at the re\ncent Minneapolis meeting of the\nUAW International board.\nHandbills have been dis\ntributed to the five Auto\nWorker Locals in Toledo telling\nthe membership that this is the\nchance they have been waiting\nthe climax to their protest\nover the strict application of the\nlittle steel formula and the in\njustices which have come out of\nWar. Labor Board rulings.\nNot A Strike\nDiscusing the meeting, UAW\nCIO Regional Director Richard\nGosser said, \u201cthis is not a strike.\nMost of the people are not work\ning on Sunday. It is a meeting\nto give our members an opportu\nnity to know what our program,\nis from now on. In Detroit, the\nworkers are on the 40-hour\nwork week with an average\ntake-home pay of $\u00b02. The same\nthing is going to occur here and\nelsewhere throughout the coun\ntry. We are going to demand\nthat something be done, and that\nthe workers receive 52 hours\npay for 40 hours work when we\nmust revert back to the 40-hour\nwork week.\u201d\nLocal Union presidents and\nother speakers will discuss the\nwage and hour problems with\nfull democratic discussion from\nthe floor of the meeting. UAW\nheads are urging their members\nto attend this important meeting\nand bring along their fellow\nworkers. The meeting will begin\nat 2:30 p. m. Local 12\u2019s baud\nwill play.\n\u2022IU ort JV Xupsinux 1OXM aunj\nOhio Officeholders\nFor Wage Raise\nCLEVELAND\" (LPA) Peti\ntions to Ohio Congressmen, ask\ning them in turn to sign a peti\ntion urging President Truman to\nlift the lid on wages by executive\norder, have been signed by\nCleveland city councilmen and\nstate representatives here. Initial\nsignatures were obtained at a\npublic meeting called by the\nCleveland Industrial Union\nCouncil, and the first to place\ntheir names on record were\nCouncilman Wilbur C. Walker\nand State Representatives Eliza\nbeth Gorman and Lody Huml.\nVol. 3, No. 36 48,000 Circulation TOLEDO, OTHO, FRIDAY, AUGUST 10, 945\nBusiness\nTax Cut\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 9\nI LPA)\u2014There won\u2019t be any\ntax, relief for the overbur\ndened little guy in the near\nfuture, but big business is\nfiguring on getting rid of its\nwartime tax obligations just as\nfast as possible and heaping the\npublic debt on the low-income\nbrackets.\nThe National Association of\nManufacturers last week asked\nfor junking of the excess profits\ntax at the end of the year when\nthe Japanese war ends. Congress\nwill also be pressured by the\nNAM to reduce the surtax rate\nof 40% on corporations to 32%\non 1946 income.\nThese demands and others\ncame on the heels of huge tax\nrefunds and Treasury handouts\nto corporations that have made\nthe greatest profits in U. S. his\ntory.\nBanking, business and trade\npublications recently have oozed\nwith confidence that Congress\nin its next session will be per\nsuaded to lighten the load on\ncorporations while retaining the\npresent taxes on lower-bracket\nincomes.\nTax Outlook Bright\nThe optimism of big business\nwas reflected in the shrewdly\nanalytical Executive Policy Let\nter (July 27) published by the\nResearch Institute of America.\nThe letter advises executives\nthat the short-range tax outlook\nis bright for them. \u201cIf the war\nends soon,\u201d the Letter asserts,\n\u201c1946 should see the end of ex\ncess profits tax, general reduc\ntion of most excise taxes, easing\nof individual surtax rates\u2014with\nthe greatest relief iu the high\nsurtax brackets.\u201d\nThe NAM called for a three\nbillion dollar reduction on cor\nporation and individual tax rates\nfor 1946 with the ancient argu\nment involving \u201crisk capital.\u201d\nReduce corporation taxes, it was\ncontended, and you will en\ncourage people to invest in new\nventures that may or may not\npay off.\nThe NAM, however, is less\nconcerned about purchasing\npower than tax handouts. H. E.\nHumphrys, Jr., of the U. S. Rub\nber Company and chairman of\nthe NAM\u2019s taxation committee,\ntold the Industrial Purchasing\nAgents Association last week\nthat, they should go to work im\nmediately on their individual\nCongressmen.\n\u2022IU -d ort \u00bbV XKpsjnm 7OXM UI \u00aeunx\n\u2019Join Union\u2019\nWASHINGTON (LPA) \u201cIt\nis the duty of working people\nto join a bona-fide labor union\nfor mutual protection and prog\ngress. They must organize for\ntheir own sake and for the wel\nfare of their families, their com\nmunity and their nation. The\nCIO has taken a long step in\nthat direction,\u201d said the Most\nReverend Robert E. Lucey,\nBishop of Texas, in a talk re\ncently.\nStrike Dynamite Seen\nIn WLB Wage Plan\nWASHINGTON, August 9 (LPA)\u2014Hope for some sort\nof relaxation of the national wage freeze rose in Washing\nton last week as it was learned that public members of the\nWar Labor Board have completed a program that will punch\none or two small holes in the strict wartime controls.\nThe revision will not mean\nthe junking of the little steel\nformula as demanded by all\nsections of organized labor nor\nwill it come even close to the\n20% increase which both CIO\nand AFL have asked.\nThe new policy, which busi\nness groups viewed with abso\nlutely no alarm, was reported to\nprovide for two changes: (1)\nWage raises even beyond the\nlimits of the little steel formula\nmay be granted when the em\nployer grants them voluntarily\nand where he gives assurance\nthat he will not seek correspond\ning price jumps, (2) Wage raises\nin exceptional cases where take\nhome pay has been drastically\nout by loss of overtime, incen\ntive pay or by downgrading.\nThese recommendations have\nbeen submitted to Economic\nStabilizer William H. Davis for\napproval. It is expected that\nthey will be incorporated into\nan executive order which will be\nissued by President Truman\nsometime after his return from\nEurope.\nOptimism in labor circles,\nhowever, was not shared by em\nployer groups and their publica\ntions. The July 27 issue of the\nExecutive Policy Letter, publish\ned by the Research Institute of\nAmerica for businessmen, stated\nconfidently that\npress reports no\nwill be allowed,\nbe an automatic\nmitting raises\n\u201cContrary to\nflat increase\nNor will there\nformula per\nto compensate\n1\nfor lost overtime.\u201d\nFringe adjustments, such as\nseverance and vacation pay.\nwill be allowed without WLB\nContinued on Page 2\nWants\nDemocratic Leader A1 e n\nBarkley demanded that Congress\ntake quick action when it re\nconvenes on such matters as full\nemployment legislation, unem\nployment compensation, taxes, a\nprogram of public construction,\nsetting u*p of more valley au\nthorities such as TVA, outlawing,\nof cartels and monopolies and\nstabilization of farm incomes.\nDespite this agenda and the\nprospect that reconversion prob\nlems will become more pressing'\nduring the summer months no\nSenator suggested that the body\nremain in session.\nSome Congressmen took junk-!\nets to Alaska (where the fishing\nis swell) and carried their fa\nmilies along. Others, at taxpay-,\ners' expense, went on vacation?\njaunts. Meanwhile the number\nof disemployed as the result of\ncutbacks, according to Sen.\nThomas (D., Utah) and other,\ngovernment officials, jumped\u2019\n100% in two months. As a re-'\nsuit a widespread movement,\namong labor and liberal groups\nhas started, to force Congress to\nreconvene as soon as possible.\nMany organizations contend that\nCongress should not have taken\na vacation,\u2014when war workers\ncannot, while such pressing\nproblems as full employment\nand unemployment compensa\ntion have to wait for lengthy\ndebates in October and No\nvember.\nTune In WTQL Thursday At 2:30 p. m.\nUAW Scores Record\nDETROIT (LPA)\u2014Union-hat\ning Congressmen had reason to\ngnash their teeth last week when\nit was disclosed that the wartime\nwork record of General Motors\nworkers and GM locals of the\nUnited Auto Worker-CIO has\nbeen 99.9994%.\nWalter P. Reuther, UAW viee\npresident, gave the Mead War\nInvestigating Committee figures\nshowing that in 1943 and 1944\ntotal man-hours lost through un\nauthorized strikes and stoppages\nin more than 100 GM plants un\nder contract with the UAW were\n6 10,000lhs of one per cent. The\nAugust 1 issue of the United\nAutomobile Worker points out\nthat \u201cThe figure is so small it\nis difficult to comprehend. Put\nting it another way, man-hours\nlost in GM plants, under UAW\ncontract during 1943 and 1944,\namounted to .0006%. In reverse\nthese figures mean that GM\nworkers in UAW plants, during\n1933 and 1934, worked 99.9994%\nof all scheduled hours.\u201d\nThe figures given to the Mead\ncommittee by Reuther came from\nofficial government sources.\nA IT OL vs. Strikes\nNEW YORK, Aug 7\n(LPA \u2014More man-days are\nlost each year by Naval,\nMarine and Coast Guard\npersonnel who are absent\nwithout leave or\nleave than are lost by\nStrikes. It\u2019s no labor leader\nwho points this out, but a\nSeaman First Class, Robert\nH. Phelps, writing in the\nAugust Harpers\u2019 Magazine.\n41\nTOLEDO UNION JOURNAL\nItupresenlinfi 58,000 CIO Member a in Xorthutftcrn Ohio\nI\nArmy Preparing For Reconversion And Postwar Labor Troubles\ncongress\nRe-Meet\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 8 (LPA)\n\u2014Vacations took precedence\nover the nation\u2019s welfare last\nweek as the Senate recessed un\ntil Oct. 8 with more than 15\nitems of domestic legislation\npushed over until fall.\n\u2019A\nover-\nHere is his comparison.\nThe Navy estimates that\nI. 1% of its personnel are\nAWOL or over leave at all\ntimes. That figures out to\nabout 14.000,000 man days\nof effective service each\nyear that are lost to the\nNavy alone. Strikes and\nlockouts, Phelps points out,\nlost .1%, a total of 8,500,\n000 man days of work in\n1944.\n\u201cThe Navy\u2019s record in\nthis war is so magnificent,\u201d\nPhelps adds, \u201cThat no one\nis inclined to criticize the\nservice because a small per\ncentage of its men go over\nthe hill. But labor also has\ndone its war job well, and\nshould not be pilloried be\ncause a few workers have\nfailed to keep the no-strike\npledge.\u201d\n'/'fa\nO\u20183B\nFirst to benefit under a new life insurance\nclause in the Commodore Perry Hotel's Union\n'contract was Mrs. Nattie Patterson, Paducah,\nKy. who drew a check for S1000 as beneficiary\nin the policy of her sister, Mrs. Cora Bell,\na former employee of the hotel who recently\nexpired. All members* of the Commodore\nPerry Hotel Unit of Local 363, United Retail,\nWholesale, Department Store Employees-CIO,\n\u25a0m -d or: 1 \u00bbv Atpsnitij. IOXM \u201cI\nis*\nUnion Membership Cites Protection\nPA CDrive Assures\nPR Referendum\n(ibtain 33.547 Signatures\nTo City Charter Amendment\nAs a result of PAC\u2019s concentrated drive seeking a\nerendum calling for the repeal of the PR system of electing\ncity councilmen, 33,547 signatures were obtained, sufficient\nto insure the charter amendment on the November ballot,\naccording to an announcement by PAC officials earlier this\nCall-In Pay Okayed\nBy WLB\nWASHINGTON (LPA)\u2014Three\nhours\u2019 pay for workers who are\ncalled in but do not work be\ncause of a\u2019stoppage by fellow\nworkers was upheld by the Na\ntional War Labor Board last\nweek. The UAW-CIO, represent\ning nearly all employes of the\nFirestone Rubber and Metal\nProducts Co. at Wyandotte,\nMich., has obtained this clause,\nand several other benefits, in\ntheir new agreement.\nWrite, Don\u2019t Ride\u2014ODT\nWASHINGTON (LPA)\u2014Gov\nernment officials too must cut\ndown on travel, says Office of\nDefense Transportation director\nCol. J. Monroe Johnson. In a\nletter to all government depart\nments and agencies he suggests\nthat other means than meetings\nbe used to inform field person\nnel of programs. He recommends\n\u201cextended use of postal and\ncommunications facilities\u201d\u2014gov\nernmentese for \u201cwrite, don\u2019t\nride.\u201d\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 8\u2014\nFormation of a new left-wing\ngroup in the Senate, organized\nto push social and labor legisla\ntion and offset the reactionary\ninfluence of anti-union Demo\ncrats and tory Republicans was\ndisclosed last week.\nWithout consulting party lead\ners. Sen. Claude Pepper and a\ndozen other liberal democrats\nagreed on the preparation of a\nbasic program. The invitation\nwas sent to 30 senators with the\nidea that the bloc would work\nfor passage of (1) the full em\nployment bill, (2) expanded so\ncial security, (3) federal aid to\neducation,\nstanding\nAn\ninitial under\nreportedly\nthe senators\nwas\nwhen\nIachieved\nPubTiahed tT IxxaJ 12 OAW-ClIO\n428 Wir.thror St.\niven Strong Backing\nTol\u00ab*lo Ohi\u00ae\nCIO\nref-\nweek.\nOfficers and members are\npleased with the results of the\nsignature drive in view of the\nshort time the petitions were\ncirculated. Petitions which were\ncirculated in March and April\nwere recalled when it was dis\nccvered that they\u2019 contained a\ntechnical error likely to result in\nrefusal to grant the referendum.\nNew Petitions Circulated\nNew petitions were drawn up\nand closely examined by com\npetent attorneys before circula\ntion was started, then with just\na few weeks in which to secure\ntl e required 13.500 valid signa\ntures required to place the PR\nrepeal proposal on the ballot,\nPAC went to work.\nOriginally, 30.000 signatures\nhad been set as the goal for the\npetition circulators on the first\npetition. When a long delay\ncaused by the faulty petitions\noccured. PAC officials insisted\nthat 30,000 signatures was still\nthe goal.\nRichard Gosser and Chairman\nClayton Rusch of PAC both ex\npressed their appreciation far\nContinued on Page 2\n..Su\nare covered by similar policies paid for by the\nhotel management and included as part of the\ncontract. Shown above left to right are Ivo\nIrwin, President, Toledo Joint Co-ncil Fred\nerick Shamberger, Hotel Commodore Perry\nauditor and personnel director, presenting the\ncheck for $1000 to Mrs, Nattie Patterson\nTeresa Adams, department steward and Ada\nHarp, President, Local 363.\nPlans\nLabor\nDay Parade\nRepresentative? of Local Un\nions and Units Of amalgamated\nUnions met on Wednesday night\nto make plans for the annual\nLabor Day Parade which will be\nheld on September 3.\nTentative plans are for hold\ning the parade in the morning\nwith a picnie to follow in the\nafternoon at Ottawa Park. Last\nyear\u2019s parade was held at night\ndue to many plants working on\nthe holiday.\nRoute for the 1945 Labor Day\nParade will probably be the\nsame as in other years beginning\nat Monroe and 22nd and march\ning east on Monroe to Summit\nNorth on Summit to Jefferson,\nand West on Jefferson 17th\nStreet.\nTo Award Prizes\nPrizes will again be offered\nthis year for the best floats in\nline, marching Unit, drum\ncorps and uniformed groups.\nAdditional prizes will be set\naside for games and other com\npetition at the picnic.\nEfforts will be made to bring\nin a prominent speaker to de\nliver the Labor Day address at\nOttawa Park. Detailed plans\nwill be announced by the Labor\nDay Committee as soon as they\nare completed.\n\u2022IU 1 \u00bb\u00a3:1 IV Xtpsjniu, qoXM \u201cI\nStore Profits\nWASHINGTON (LPA)\u2014Pro\nfits of department stores and\nspecialty stores are soaring in\nwartime. \u201cThose stores used to\nget llic profit on each dollar on\nsales,\u201d reports Donald Mont\ngomery, chairman of the CIO\nCost of Living Committee. \u201cThat\nwas before the war. Now, they\nare making 11 %c on each dol\nlar of sales.\u201d\nft-Wing Bloc Is\nqanized In The Senate\nagreed that whenever two or\nmore of their group introduced\nbills that were substantially the\nsame the group would work out\nan omnibus measure.\nCreation of the bloc was seen\nin some quarters as evidence of\na growing distrust in the trend\naway from liberalism manifested\nby the Truman administration.\nHowever, Sen. Pepper dis\nclaimed this and contended that\n\u201cThe president would be in this\ngroup if he still was in the Sen\nate.\u201d Sen. Magnuson (D Wash.)\nsaid that the bloc would shape\na legislative schedule to be pre\nsented to Congressional Demo\ncratic leaders as a minimum pro\ngram for action.\nSeveral members of the new\nleft-wing group have privately\nexpressed apprehension over\nsome of President Truman\u2019s re\ncent appointments and voiced\nconcern that they indicate art\nominous swing toward the right\nand'toward conciliation of Con\ngressmen known for their en\nmity to labor and liberal ideas.\nIf the Senatorial left-wing\ngroup continues and flourishes it\nis expected that it will push\nheavily for increased unemploy\nment compensation and tighen\ning of the surplus property dis\nposal law. Among the senators\nprominent in formation of the\ngroup were Mead (D., N. Y.),\nFulbright (D., Ark), Mitchell\n(D., Wash.), Kilgore (D., W.\nVai), Murray (D., Mont.), Tay\nlor (D., Idaho.)\nThe Voice of the\nCIO in\nNorthwestern\nOhio\nLeek of Jobs\nEndangers\nDemocracy\nWASHINGTON, July 7\n(LPA) Senate hearings on\nthe Full Employment Bill got\nunder way last week with a\nringing challenge by Sen.\nRobert Wagner (D. N. Y.) that\nEither we must conquer unem\nployment, or unemployment will\ndestroy our freedom.\u201d\nWagner was joined in vigor\nous support of the bill by Sena\ntors Murray D. Mont.), Thomas\n(D. Utah), and O\u2019Mahoney (D.\nWyo.) All four are sponsors of\nthe legislation and appeared be\nfore a subcommittee of the Sen\nate Banking Currency Com\nmittee which is headed by Sen.\nWagner. In addition three Re\npublican senators pledged their\nsupport: Morse of Oregon, Tobey\nof New Hampshire, and Aiken\nof Vermont\nAs a result the full employ\nment bill got a strong start with\nthe probability that it will pick\nup many other Congressional\nsupporters before hearings rec\nommence in the fall. In October\nthe subcommittee will hear rep\nresentatives of organized labor,\nveterans, religious, business and\nfarm groups.\nSpurred by English\nSpurred by the Labor Party\u2019s\noverthrow of the Churchill gov\nernment and also by predictions\nby government economists that\nthe nation can expect a possible\n12,000.000 unemployed after V-J\nDay, the* subcommittee tackled\nthe proposed legislation with\ngrim earnestness.\nSen. Murray, after comment\ning on the British upheaval, de\nclared \u201cIn the days to come I\ncan see nothing but conflict and\nrecrimination for capitalism in\nAmerica unless we provide a\nprogram which will insure em-\nContinued on Page 2\n'appy\u2019AIoves\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 7 (LPA)\n\u2014Senator Pappy O\u2019Daniel, Texas\nrabble-rouser and labor-hater,\nhas moved the headquarters of\nhis union-busting newspaper, the\n\u2022W. Lee ODaniel News'\" from\nFort Worth to Washington and\ninstalled his staff in an impres\nsive bank building which he\nswapped for property in Texas.\nThe former flour salesman\nconducted reporters through the\nbank building with its high\nvaulted ceiling and assured them\nthat the paper, although edited\nfrom Washington instead of Fort\nWorth, would continue the pol\nicies that have drawn fire not\nonly from labor and liberal\ngroups but also from his Con\ngressional colleagues.\nA weekly, eight-page standard\nfize newspaper, the O'Daniel\nNews was founded five years\nago. According to the Senator it\nnow reaches more than 100,000\nreaders at a cost of S5 a year,\n\u2022tu iv Xtpsinux injM uj aun\u00a3\nCIO Man Named\nTo Labor Dept.\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 8 (LPA)\n\u2014The CIO got its first real foot\nhold in the Labor Dept, last\nweek when Secretary Schwellen\nbach announced the appointment\nof John W. Gibson, president of\nthe Michigan CIO, as special as\nsistant. The AFL already has its\nrepresentative in Ass\u2019t Labor\nSecretary Dan Tracy from the\nInternational Brotherhood of\nElectrical Workers.\nSchwellenbach\u2019s announcement\nsaid that Gibson \u201cwill be asso\nciated\u201d with Moran and Tracy\n\u201cin the task of reorganizing the\nLabor Dept Gibson, one of the\nmost respected CIO leaders in\nthe country, was chairman of\nthe Michigan State Dept, of La\nbor and Industries from 1941 to\n1943.\nAlong with Gibson's appoint\nment Schwellenbach also\nAlbert Abrahamson of\nswick. Me., as another\nassistant to assist Moran\nadministration of the depart\nment. Xbrahamson, was an asso\nciate professor of economics at\nBowdoin College until 1934. He\nwas WPA administrator\nin Maine from 1935 to 1937 and\nassistant executive\nthe War Refugee\nthis appointment.\n1\nPrice 5c\n4\n1\n\u25a0i\n,1*\nnamed\nBrun\nspecial\nin the\ndirector of\nBoard until","height":"26955","width":"20454"}}
